Question 1

Suppose we have a data set with five predictors, \(X_{1}=\text{GPA}\), \(X_{2}=\text{IQ}\), \(X_{3}=\text{Level ( 1 for College and 0 for High School)}\), \(X_{4}=\textrm{Interaction between GPA and IQ}\), and \(X_{5}=\text{Interaction between GPA and Level}\). The response is starting salary after graduation (in thousands of dollars). Suppose we use least squares to fit the model, and get \(\hat{\beta}_{0}=50\), \(\hat{\beta}_{1}=20\), \(\hat{\beta}_{2}=0.07\), \(\hat{\beta}_{3}=35\), \(\hat{\beta}_{4}=0.01\), \(\hat{\beta}_{5}=-10\).

  1. Which answer is correct, and why?
    1. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, high school graduates earn more, on average, than college graduates.
    2. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, college graduates earn more, on average, than high school graduates.
    3. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, high school graduates earn more, on average, than college graduates provided that the GPA is high enough.
    4. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, college graduates earn more, on average, than high school graduates provided that the GPA is high enough.

3 is true because the only two terms that are changing are X3 and X5, and when the level is 0, X5 cancels out, or when theres a college graduate, any GPA above a 3.5 has high schoolers make more money because of Beta5 being negative a higher GPA negatively impacts a college graduates salary. But at exactly 3.5, -35 cancelled out 35 of X3 and then the other termd are fixed so theres no change.

  1. Predict the salary of a college graduate with IQ of 110 and a GPA of 4.0.
b0 = 50
b1 = 20
b2 = .07
b3 = 35
b4 = .01
b5 = -10

salary = function(IQ, GPA, LVL){
  x = b0+ b1*GPA + b2*IQ +b3*LVL + b4*IQ*GPA + b5*GPA*LVL
  return(x)
    
}
salary(110, 4, 1)
## [1] 137.1
  1. True or false: Since the coefficient for the GPA/IQ interaction term is very small, there is very little evidence of an interaction effect. Justify your answer. ### False. Statistical significance of an interaction is different than the size of the interaction. Small coefficient doesnt mean effect is small because its impacted by the size of the two variables.

Question 2

I collect a set of data (\(n=100\) observations) containing a single predictor and a quantitative response. I then fit a linear regression model to the data, as well as a separate cubic regression, i.e. \(Y=\) \(\beta_{0}+\beta_{1} X+\beta_{2} X^{2}+\beta_{3} X^{3}+\epsilon\)

  1. Suppose that the true relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\) is linear, i.e. \(Y=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1} X+\epsilon\). Consider the training residual sum of squares (RSS) for the linear regression, and also the training RSS for the cubic regression. Would we expect one to be lower than the other, would we expect them to be the same, or is there not enough information to tell? Justify your answer. ### I would expect the polynomial regression to have a lower training RSS than the linear regression because it could make a tighter fit against the data that has a wider epsilon.

  2. Answer a. using test rather than training RSS. ### I would expect the polynomial regression to have a higher test RSS because the overfit from training has more error than the linear regression. A cubic model would be overfitting because we know the true relationsuip is linear.

  3. Suppose that the true relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\) is not linear, but we dont know how far it is from linear. Consider the training RSS for the linear regression, and also the training RSS for the cubic regression. Would we expect one to be lower than the other, would we expect them to be the same, or is there not enough information to tell? Justify your answer. ### Cubic regression will have a lower training RSS than the linear regression because of its high flexibility. The more flexible model will follow points better and reduce the training RSS.

  4. Answer (c) using test rather than training RSS. ### There is not enough information to tell which test RSS would be lower for either regression, as we do not know how not linear it is. Because of the bias-variance tradeoff, we dont know what level of flexibility will fit this data better.

Question 3

Suppose we collect data for a group of students in a statistics class with variables \(X_{1}=\text{hours studied}\), \(X_{2}=\text{undergrad GPA}\), and \(Y=\text{receive an A}\). We fit a logistic regression and produce estimated coefficient, \(\hat{\beta}_{0}=-6, \hat{\beta}_{1}=0.05, \hat{\beta}_{2}=1\).

  1. Estimate the probability that a student who studies for \(40\mathrm{h}\) and has an undergrad GPA of \(3.5\) gets an A in the class.
b_knot = -6
b1 = 0.05
b2 = 1

y <-function(X1, X2){
  y_log <- b_knot+b1*X1 + b2*X2
  prob_of_A <- 1/(1 + exp(-y_log))
  return(prob_of_A)
}
y(40, 3.5)
## [1] 0.3775407
  1. How many hours would the student in part a. need to study to have a \(50\%\) chance of getting an A in the class?
y <-function(X1, X2){
  y_log <- b_knot+b1*X1 + b2*X2
  prob_of_A <- 1/(1 + exp(-y_log))
  return(prob_of_A)
}
y(50, 3.5)
## [1] 0.5
